Document: handling_quit_requests
Path: godot/tutorials/inputs/handling_quit_requests.rst
Summary: Explains how applications can handle quit requests across different platforms.

Quitting
Most platforms have the option to request the application to quit. On desktops, this is usually done with the "x" icon on the window title bar. On mobile devices, the app can quit at any time while it is suspended to the background.
---CHUNK---
Document: Handling the notification
Path: godot/tutorials/inputs/handling_quit_requests.rst
Summary: How to handle window manager quit requests in Godot using the NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST notification.

On desktop and web platforms, Node receives a special NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST notification when quitting is requested from the window manager. Handling the notification is done as follows (on any node):

GDScript:
    func _notification(what):
        if what == NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST:
            get_tree().quit() # default behavior

C#:
    public override void _Notification(int what)
    {
        if (what == NotificationWMCloseRequest)
        {
            GetTree().Quit(); // default behavior
        }
    }

Note: By default, Godot apps quit when a window manager quit request is received. This can be changed to allow custom quitting procedures:

GDScript:
    get_tree().set_auto_accept_quit(false)

C#:
    GetTree().AutoAcceptQuit = false;
---CHUNK---
Document: Handling Quit Requests  
Path: godot/tutorials/inputs/handling_quit_requests.rst  
Summary: How to handle app closure and suspension events on mobile platforms in Godot.  

On mobile platforms, there is no direct equivalent to NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST. Due to mobile operating system constraints, the only reliable way to execute code before quitting is during app suspension. Both Android and iOS may kill suspended apps at any time, so use NOTIFICATION_APPLICATION_PAUSED to perform critical actions when the app transitions to the background. Note: On iOS, tasks initiated by this signal must complete within approximately 5 seconds, or iOS will terminate the app instead of pausing it. On Android, pressing the Back button triggers NOTIFICATION_WM_GO_BACK_REQUEST and exits the application if the **Application > Config > Quit On Go Back** setting is enabled (default behavior).
---CHUNK---
Document: Handling Quit Requests  
Path: godot/tutorials/inputs/handling_quit_requests.rst  
Summary: How to properly notify the scene tree of an upcoming quit request before closing the application.  

Calling SceneTree.quit directly forces the application to close without sending the NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST to nodes, skipping custom quit actions like saving or confirmation. To ensure nodes can respond to termination, manually propagate the notification first:  

GDScript:  
get_tree().root.propagate_notification(NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST)  

C#:  
GetTree().Root.PropagateNotification((int)NotificationWMCloseRequest);  

This notifies all nodes of the impending quit but does not terminate the program. Key Rule: In Godot 4.X, propagating NOTIFICATION_WM_CLOSE_REQUEST does not terminate the program, unlike in 3.X. Call SceneTree.quit afterward to close the application. Note: Using SceneTree.quit directly skips custom quit actions like saving or confirmation.